The European Union changes the rules for the obtainment of the visa
The people must go to the centers of Service for the Plaintiffs of Visa before their interview in the Consular Section; the cout the time of waiting more will be reduced.
From January 10th, 2011 the procedure of treatment of the visas at the Embassy and consulates of the United States will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of plaintiffs will have to appear to the centers of Service for the Plaintiffs of Visa (ASC, according to his acronyms in English) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The staff of ASC will take the biometrical information of the plaintiff, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will present some advantages for the candidates, among which one mentions the next ones:
The total cost to treat the visa will be lower, making a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the treatment of the visa and another so that the service of mail delivers the document will not be no more necessary.
The candidate will realize a unique payment that will cover the three services.
The present price will remain the same one: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a visa of tourist, 150 dollars in the case of visas with request (ci-inclut the visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for the visas of storekeepers and investors.
The people who want to renew their visa will not have to appear to one interview with the Consular Representative, they will appear only to the ASC closer where they will present the documents and one will take their imprinted.
Because of the fact that the biometrical information will be busy in the ASC, the plaintiffs who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain less time than beforehand.
Similarly, the plaintiffs of visa to the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will not pay anymore the price extra on duty of 26 dollars.
For other information on the new procedure to solicit the visa, visit the page next http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
