Climate: how does France fiddle with his promises of financings
A year after the Agreement of Copenhagen, it is time of examining the respect of the promises of rapidly unblocked financings (said financings fast start or precocious) realized by the developed countries.
And the big French bidouillages are revealed.
In the agreement of Copenhagen, the developed countries have committed to supplying 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7,2 billion euros on three years and France 1,26 billions of euros (is 420 million per annum).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has taken out the great game to persuade his partners of the reality of his commitment regarding the fast start financings: relation detailing the action of his Member States, press conference, great side event, distribution of booklets...
The transparency operation is appreciable and appreciated to his fair value: the developping countries and the non-trading company would love that all the developed countries follow suit with a same level of precision.
The EU announces to have freed in 2010 2,2 billion from euros, what puts it on the good path for the respect of his commitment of 7,2 billion in 2012.
But while one looks in the detail, the things are complicated more.
This money must be, according to the agreement of Copenhagen, "new and additional," in order to assure that an additional effort is realized without being public to the detriment of the Help to the development.
Unfortunately, it does not exist agreed on what means "new and additional."
Even though the European Commission had proposed a harmonization, some Member States of which France have blocked the procedure.
Today, each chooses the reference that suits it the best.
The European Commission has for example considered as reference the year 2009: the international financings are maintained, and it adds 150 million to it towards three years to the title of the fast start financings.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or in terms of level of public help to the development.
On the Other Hand, France considers that the financings of "all the new projects" of the year 2010 are "new and additional."
In other words, there is not reference to the expenses of the previous years or at the global level of public Help to the development.
Concretely, the total amount of the support of France at the developping countries can remain stable (or even to diminish), she claims to respect his commitment as regards "new and additional" financings...
Other crucial element, the distribution between gifts and loans.
There still, there is not rule and each chooses his way of calculation.
Some, as France, consider lent qu'1€ is tantamount at 1 € given.
Evidently, that is in a difficult way justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments that are profitable (often of the projects related to the alleviation of the emissions that rest on more efficient technologies), presenting a euro that one is going to recover as equivalent to a euro that one gives is fallacious... At most, should not be counted to the title of his commitments only the cost of the loan for the lending country (is the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France does not have that to make of such a reasoning: it "respects" his commitment of 420 million euros making 91,5% of loans (389,8 million euros) and 8,5% of gifts (36,1 million euros) - to see the document of the EU to verify by yourself.
It is the only country of the Union to use so massively the loan.
Germany summons to 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or the Slovakia (in other) respect their commitments with 100% of gifts.
In other words, when the very great majority of the European Union takes 1 € to satisfy his commitment, France takes only 10 centimes and considers that the effort is comparable.
Pretty trick!
In summary, in his fast start financing, France operates on a double swindle: on the one hand on the evolution of the action in the time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
Using only 36,1 million euros, she manages to make to believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in coherence with his promises.
The handling of the ministry of the Finances (because it seems well that it is Bercy that has realized the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why the other Member States would continue fall if stretching suffices?) and in the negotiations since the developping countries are not completely dupe...
The chapter of the precocious financings is only a small question, of short relative term, in relation to the unity of the discussions on the climate.
But it could be a grain of sand more in the immense machine than the UNFCCC is.
Hope that that will not be the case.
Which that it is, it is essential to get out the lessons of this first year of precocious financings.
First and Foremost, the France could announce a change in his way of comptabilisation for the years 2011 and 2012, in a mind of respect of his commitments and of equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But especially, the France could make advance the discussions on the stakes of financings in the long term (other crucial chapter discussed presently): one will not escape the question of "the additionalité" or of the way of comptabilisation of the loans.
France could change his position for also progressive evolution on these stakes as it is it on others.
The hope rests therefore on the new minister of the Environment, Mme Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive to Cancun next week.
An announcement discovered on the fast start of France and on his vision of "the additionalité" and the use of loans would be by nature to increase the level in trust international necessary to advance in the discussions.
